<dl id="un7030f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un7" href="#un7030">UN7: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un7all.htm#un7030f"> (V.A.2) 30(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> limit,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It used to be thought that &ldquo;<mark>limit</mark>&rdquo; was an essentially quantitative notion, namely, the notion of a quantity to which others approached nearer and nearer, so that among those others there would be some differing by less than any assigned quantity. But in fact the notion of &ldquo;limit&rdquo; is a purely ordinal notion, not involving quantity at all (except by accident when the series concerned happens to be quantitative). <small> Bertrand Russell, <a name="BRIM" href="/udra/udex.htm#brim"><cite title="source">Introduction to Mathematical Philosophy</cite></a> (1919), 97</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
